The default bridge network.

When you install Docker, you get three networks out of the box, plus a Linux bridge called docker-zero on the host. If you list the networks, you'll see bridge, with the bridge driver; host, with the host driver; and none, with the null driver. Every container you start without the network flag joins that default bridge.

It works, but it has two limitations that make it the wrong choice for anything real.

The first: no embedded d-n-s. Containers on the default bridge can only reach each other by eye-pee address. If you run one container named web and another named a-p-i, then from inside web, the hostname a-p-i does not resolve. You'd have to dig the address out of docker inspect. And that's brittle, because addresses change when containers restart.

The second: weak isolation. Every container without an explicit network flag shares this one bridge. So an unrelated container that you spun up for a quick test can talk to your dev Postgres, simply because both landed on docker-zero.

The takeaway is short. The default bridge is a historical default; don't rely on it. The moment two containers need to talk, create a user-defined bridge, which is the next section, and which fixes both problems at once: name-based d-n-s, and per-network isolation. You'll essentially never choose the default bridge on purpose. It's just where containers fall when you forget to say otherwise.
